Crypt Stalkers — The Vault
The History (in three layers)
Layer 1: The Salt Mines (centuries ago)
A productive salt mine, worked for generations. Tunnels, shafts, processing chambers, miners' barracks. Mundane, profitable, unremarkable. The deepest galleries reached salt deposits of unusual purity — the kind that, in folklore, was said to ward against evil. The miners knew the stories. They didn't take them seriously.

Layer 2: The Demonologist's Tower (generations later, after the mine was abandoned)
A scholar named Veyran Mott acquired the abandoned mine and built a tower at its surface entrance. He'd chosen the site deliberately — pure salt below, isolation above, a prepared underground complex no one would investigate. He spent decades preparing a single ritual: the binding and summoning of an arch-demon. He needed the salt to contain what he was calling. He didn't intend to release it. He intended to own it.

He nearly succeeded. The summoning reached its final stages. The arch-demon was almost through. And then the Order arrived.

Layer 3: The Order's Vault (the present day, six hundred years later)
The Order of the Pale Vigil arrived in time to interrupt the summoning, but not in time to undo it. The arch-demon was caught in the threshold — not free, not dismissed, locked in the moment of arrival. Sethara, the Order's founder, recognized the situation immediately. The summoning could not be reversed. The demon could not be banished from a partial state. But it could be held — indefinitely, if the containment was perfect.

She used the demonologist's own materials against him. The pure salt from the deepest galleries was carved, blessed, and arranged into a barrier in the shape of the Order's holy symbol. The mine became a vault. The tower became a chapter house. The Order vowed to maintain the containment forever.

Sethara sealed herself inside as the anchor. The Order interred its dead within to fill the containment with bodies the demon could not use as vessels.

Six centuries passed.

The Areas
1. Excursion Tunnels (introduction)
In-world purpose: Recently dug by undead inhabitants to raid nearby towns for resources — primarily salt. The barrier is degrading; salt is being consumed faster than the Order replaces it; the dungeon's inhabitants are improvising.

Narrative purpose: First impression. The player enters here because Aldric's letter directs them to a side breach — not the main entrance. The Excursion Tunnels show that something is wrong: undead are leaving the vault, organized, with purpose, in defiance of everything the Order's surface doctrine claims is possible.

Layout: Narrow, freshly dug, irregular. Distinct from the rest of the dungeon (which is centuries-old construction). Pickaxe marks. Hastily braced ceilings. The tunnels feel new.

Clues encountered:

Pickaxes alongside corpses — undead were digging, recently
Salt residue on tools and on the dead themselves — they were carrying it back inward
A torn raid map of nearby villages, with salt suppliers circled
A Vigil sigil dropped in the dirt — Aldric came through here
Inhabitants: Skeletons and zombies in organized work groups along the main corridors; rats colonizing the sides where excavation debris piles up.

Connects to: Salt Barrier (inward), Barracks (the work groups return here)

Mechanics introduced: Basic combat. Skeleton reform problem. The MC's pierce/slash weapon is inadequate. They survive their first expedition by retreating, not winning.

2. The Entrance (Aldric's path)
In-world purpose: The original ceremonial entry to the vault. Massive holy gates, reinforced, sealed. Hasn't been opened since the vault was built — except by Grandmasters.

Narrative purpose: This is where Aldric entered. The player can reach it via the Excursion Tunnels or via Aldric's key (the front door). The Entrance is a secondary route, but it bypasses some of the Excursion Tunnel's chaos and provides early lore about the Order's original protocols.

Layout: A grand antechamber. Cracked frescoes depicting the Order's founding (only partially intelligible without later context). A massive door, opened recently by Aldric's key — still ajar.

Clues encountered:

Frescoes showing Sethara, the demon (depicted as a threshold, not a creature), and the salt barrier being built
An inscription with the Order's first oath — early version of the Warden's Oath
Aldric's discarded outer cloak. He left it here. He was traveling lighter.
Connects to: The Mausoleum (inward through ceremonial passages)

3. The Mausoleum (the Order's purpose, made literal)
In-world purpose: Where the Order's dead are received, prepared, and turned. The largest section of the upper vault by volume, but with surprisingly few intact tombs — because corpses are processed quickly, not stored.

Layout:

The Chimney: A vertical shaft from the surface chapter house. Bodies are lowered down it. The shaft is plugged at the top with a heavy stone seal that only the Grandmaster can open. The MC can see daylight at the very top — the chapter house they came from.
The Preparation Room: Stone slabs, ritual tools, dried herbs (centuries old, still potent). Where Vigil morticians readied bodies. The Interment Maul is here, alongside other mortician tools.
The Ritual Room: Where bodies were turned into wardens. Inscribed circles on the floor. The walls are covered in the interment prayer — the rite the morticians spoke during conversion. This is the inscription the MC brings to Sable to learn Lay to Rest.
Clues encountered:

The interment prayer (full text — taught to morticians, not knights)
Mortician's logs: who was interred, when, where they were positioned
A gap in the logs covering the last few decades — recordkeeping has lapsed as the Order declined
Aldric's notes in the margin of a recent log: "Position 47-South empty since 1218. Why?"
Inhabitants: Decayed wardens — first-generation undead, barely functional, performing the routines of preparation on each other in endless loops. Skeletons mostly. The mausoleum is the bone-source for everything else.

What you find here: Interment Maul, Lay to Rest (via Sable), the Interment Pattern (via Imber), and the understanding that the Order's dead are workers, not victims.

Connects to: Excursion Tunnels (the breach point), The Libraries, Maintenance corridors

4. The Libraries (history and transferable knowledge)
In-world purpose: Where the Order kept its knowledge — the Vigil's training texts, Sethara's research, copies of the Demonologist's confiscated work, and centuries of maintenance logs.

Narrative purpose: This is where the player learns what the dungeon actually is. Not all at once — the libraries are fragmented, partially burned (in places), and some sections are deliberately warded against intrusion.

Sub-sections:

The Public Stacks: Vigil training material. Knights of the order would have studied here. Useful but mundane.
The Restricted Stacks: Sethara's research, sealed away from junior knights. Contains her early journals (the schism, her grief, her decision), her technical notes on the containment, and the original History of the Site (salt mine → demonologist → vault).
The Demonologist's Wing: Confiscated material from Veyran Mott. Books in unfamiliar scripts, ritual diagrams, his personal journals. The Order kept these because Sethara believed understanding the original ritual might one day be necessary to reverse it. She was right.
The Artifact Vault (sub-area, see below)
Clues encountered:

The full history: salt mines, Veyran Mott, the partial summoning, the construction of the barrier
Hints at the nature of the arch-demon — never named, never described in full, but referenced obliquely in margin notes that read like someone afraid to write the wrong word
Sethara's personal log of the early decades — her loneliness, her resolve, her realization that the binding was changing her
Veyran Mott's journals — frighteningly lucid, methodical, not insane. He believed he was saving humanity by binding the demon to a human will. He was wrong.
Inhabitants: Wraiths (the only enemy in this zone — bound to the books they wrote or studied in life, repeating their last thoughts), the occasional Crypt Stalker assigned to library patrol.

Mechanics introduced: Knowledge gates. The library is where the player begins synthesizing fragments. Each significant text found can be brought to a Cairnsmouth NPC for translation/contextualization, unlocking abilities, items, or map information.

4a. The Artifact Vault (sub-area of the Libraries)
In-world purpose: Where dangerous objects were stored — items confiscated from the Demonologist, items the Order created and didn't trust outside the vault, items found in the salt mines that predate everything.

Narrative purpose: Risk/reward zone. High-value loot, high-difficulty defenders. Some items here are critical to the late-game endings.

Contents:

The Sanctified Mace is forged from a Demonologist's ritual implement, here, after Sable provides the rite
A salt-iron blade — pure salt fused with iron, never tarnishes, deals bonus damage to anything demonically touched (Wailing Shades, the Vampire Lord, the demon itself in the final encounter)
The Demonologist's Compass — points toward the demon, regardless of where you are. Useful for navigation in the deep vault. Also slowly drives the bearer toward obsession the longer they carry it
Veyran Mott's personal grimoire — the only complete record of the original summoning. Required for the third ending. Reading it inflicts persistent psychological pressure (mechanically: minor ongoing penalty until the player decides whether to use the knowledge)
Inhabitants: A unique Crypt Stalker — Sethara's first lieutenant, interred here specifically to guard this room. Possibly the hardest non-boss encounter in the game.

Connects to: Libraries only. Single entrance, heavily warded.

5. Maintenance (the vault's internal infrastructure)
In-world purpose: Service corridors used by the Vigil's maintenance crews — ventilation, water lines, salt resupply routes, structural supports. The vault is not a passive structure; it requires constant upkeep.

Narrative purpose: This zone shows the player how badly things are decaying. It's the connective tissue of the dungeon, and it's falling apart.

Layout: Cramped service tunnels connecting the major zones. Faster transit between areas if you know the routes. Many of the tunnels are blocked by collapses, broken pumps, or the bodies of maintenance crews who died in place.

Clues encountered:

Maintenance logs showing the gradual decline: "salt resupply delayed 30 days," "ward circle 12 inactive, no replacement available," "warden positions 47-S, 51-S, 52-N empty"
Tools — pickaxes, salt-carrying bags, maintenance manuals
The bodies of maintenance crews — living Vigil members who died down here in the last few decades, sent in by previous Grandmasters and not returned. None of them are interred properly. Some have become Wailing Shades.
Inhabitants: Wailing Shades (the unburied dead, partially claimed by the demon's pressure), the occasional roving Crypt Stalker on patrol.

Mechanics introduced:

Maintenance routes — once mapped, allow faster travel between zones (skip rooms you've cleared)
Salt scarcity — the player can find caches of salt here, used as a resource for re-blessing the barrier (see late-game)
The realization that the Order has been sending knights down here secretly for years — and none came back. Aldric is one of many.
Connects to: Mausoleum, Libraries, Barracks, Old Salt Mines

6. Barracks (the dungeon's organized intelligence)
In-world purpose: Where the Order's living garrison was originally housed during the vault's construction. After Sethara sealed herself in, the barracks were repurposed as a coordination point for the wardens. Now they function as the headquarters of the dungeon's organized raiding force.

Narrative purpose: Reveals that the dungeon's inhabitants are coordinated — not individual monsters, but an organized faction with goals. Specifically: they're trying to maintain the containment from the inside, despite their degraded state. They raid for salt because the barrier needs salt. They organize because Sethara is fading and someone has to do the work.

Layout: Functional military architecture — bunk rooms, mess halls, planning chambers, a central command room with maps of the surrounding region and the vault itself.

Clues encountered:

Raid plans, written in a deteriorating Vigil script — undead following old protocols
Maps showing salt sources, raid routes, optimal timing
A central "command map" of the vault showing which positions are filled, which are empty, which sections are compromised
A lieutenant's journal — written by an undead who retains enough self to write. The journal documents the slow loss of self, the commitment to duty even as memory fades, and the awareness that Sethara is no longer responding to requests for orders. This is the closest thing the player gets to a "good" undead — a mind hanging on out of sheer discipline.
Inhabitants: Crypt Stalkers (in highest concentration), Necromancers (acting as field commanders), organized squads of skeletons and zombies executing patrol routes.

The Lieutenant (unique encounter): An ancient Crypt Stalker who still retains enough awareness to parley. The MC, once they have the Warden's Oath and the Warden's Seal, can speak with him. He provides critical information about the state of the containment, the location of key resources, and the nature of the breach — if the MC can convince him they're a legitimate authority.

Connects to: Excursion Tunnels (raid launching point), Maintenance, Old Salt Mines

7. Old Salt Mines (the deepest pre-Order layer)
In-world purpose: The original purpose of the site. Vast galleries of pure crystalline salt, with mining infrastructure (lifts, carts, miners' shrines) still in place. Extends far beneath the vault proper.

Narrative purpose: Reminds the player that this site existed before anything supernatural. The salt is the foundation of everything — the demonologist chose this place for the salt, the Order built the barrier from this salt, and salt is what's running out.

Layout: Open, vast, vertical. Different from the cramped vault corridors above. The mines have their own scale — galleries the size of cathedrals, narrow shafts dropping hundreds of feet, ancient rope-and-pulley systems still functional.

Mechanics introduced:

Vertical traversal — descending requires rope (consumed) or working lifts (require maintenance)
Salt harvesting — the player can mine raw salt themselves with a pickaxe (found here). Raw salt is the most valuable resource for late-game progression — it's required to repair the Salt Barrier
Rich loot — pre-Order, pre-demon. Miners' caches. Lost equipment. Things that have been here for centuries undisturbed because the dead don't come this deep (the salt repels them)
Inhabitants: Almost nothing. Salt repels the undead. The mines are safe in a way nowhere else in the vault is. The threat here is environmental: collapses, drowning in flooded galleries, getting lost in the dark, falls.

The miners' shrines — small altars where miners left offerings to whatever they prayed to. These are pre-Order, pre-Vigil. They contain the only inscriptions in the vault that have nothing to do with the demon, the Order, or Sethara. They're the only places in the dungeon where the player can rest and feel completely safe — protected by mundane salt, not by anything that requires their blood or their oath.

Connects to: Maintenance, Barracks (the undead avoid the deep mines but raid the upper galleries for salt), The Salt Barrier

8. The Salt Barrier (the containment itself)
In-world purpose: The physical structure that holds the demon in place. Built from carved salt blocks arranged in the shape of the Order's holy symbol. Surrounds the Demonologist's Tower at the heart of the dungeon. The barrier is the load-bearing reality of the containment — everything else (the wardens, the Necromancers, the Lich) exists to maintain it.

Narrative purpose: The player sees, finally, what they've been protecting. The barrier is enormous, beautiful, and visibly degrading. Cracks. Worn carvings. Sections where the salt has been chipped away by raiders desperate for material to repair other sections. It's a structure being held together by patches.

Layout: A vast circular chamber. The barrier walls form the perimeter. The Demonologist's Tower rises at the center, accessible only by passing through a single ceremonial gate in the barrier. Around the inside of the barrier are the Wardens of the Threshold — the most powerful Crypt Stalkers, positioned permanently as load-bearing components of the containment.

Clues encountered:

Cracks. Lots of cracks. Some patched with hastily-blessed iron. Some patched with raw salt. Some not patched at all.
The bodies of Vigil knights who died trying to repair the barrier without knowing how. Aldric is not among them — but you can see where he stopped, where he stood, where he looked at the barrier and understood.
A maintenance manual carved into the barrier itself, in Sethara's hand — instructions for restoring sections. Critical late-game knowledge.
Inhabitants: Wardens of the Threshold — Crypt Stalkers permanently bound to the barrier. They are the strongest non-boss enemies in the game. They cannot leave their positions. They can be fought one at a time, but each one removed weakens the barrier.

Mechanics introduced:

Barrier repair — the player can use raw salt + sanctified oil + the maintenance manual to repair cracks. This is the only mechanic in the game that improves the dungeon. It strengthens the containment, weakens the breach pressure, and is required for the "good" endings.
The strategic choice: every Warden of the Threshold removed weakens the containment further. The player can fight through them (faster, more dangerous, ends with a worse outcome) or find ways around them (slower, requires Dead Stillness and patience, preserves the barrier).
Connects to: Old Salt Mines (only way in for the player — through the bottom, where the barrier was built on top of mining tunnels), The Demonologist's Tower (single ceremonial gate)

9. The Demonologist's Tower (the center)
In-world purpose: Where Veyran Mott performed his summoning. Where the arch-demon is suspended in its half-arrival. Where Sethara made her choice. Where she still is.

Narrative purpose: The endgame zone. Smaller than the others, denser, stranger. Reality bends here. The Wailing Dark is at its strongest. The demon is almost present.

Layout: A vertical tower, originally Veyran's workspace, now repurposed as Sethara's anchor point. Multiple floors, each more affected by the breach than the last:

Ground floor: Veyran's old library and ritual prep room. Mostly intact. The history of the summoning is here.
Middle floors: Sethara's living quarters from her early decades, then her workspace, then her sanctum. The further up you go, the more the rooms reflect her decline — orderly, then disordered, then strange.
Top floor: The summoning chamber. The breach. Sethara. The demon.
Inhabitants: Wailing Shades (densest concentration in the game), Sethara herself in the final chamber. The Lich is not encountered as a roaming enemy — she is waiting.

The encounter with Sethara is not a simple boss fight. It's a multi-phase encounter that depends on what the player has learned and brought:

If the player has the Veil Tincture only: They can survive the chamber and fight her. Brutal combat. Killing her collapses the containment. Bad ending — the demon arrives.
If the player has the Warden's Seal and the Warden's Oath: Sethara recognizes the chain of authority. She speaks. She tells the player the truth — all of it. They can choose to fight, succeed her, or attempt the third path.
If the player has Veyran Mott's grimoire: The third path opens. The original summoning can be reversed — but only by performing it backward, which requires the demon's name (in the grimoire), the original ritual circle (in the summoning chamber), and pure salt (from the mines). Sethara, freed of her duty, finally dies.
10. The Lich's Lair (within the Tower)
In-world purpose: Sethara's actual physical location — the central anchor point of the containment. She is bound here, not by chains but by her own ritual. She cannot leave. She has not left in six hundred years.

Narrative purpose: Final encounter. The truth. The choice.

What's in the room:

Sethara, seated, ringed by salt
The arch-demon, visible only as a wrongness in the air at the center of the chamber — neither here nor not-here
The original summoning circle, half-erased, half-active
A single chair across from Sethara, where the player sits if they came in peace
The journals she wrote and never finished, scattered around her
The arch-demon itself is never fully seen. The player gets impressions: scale, hunger, patience. It is not a creature to fight in the conventional sense. The "boss fight" of the final encounter, if there is one, is between the player and Sethara — not the demon. The demon is the stakes, not the opponent.

