This is a much stronger foundation. The three-layer history gives the dungeon real archaeological depth, and salt as the key resource is the kind of concrete, physical detail that makes everything else feel grounded. Let me work through the implications.

Crypt Stalkers — The Salt Vault
The Three Histories
Every room in the dungeon belongs to one of three eras. Players can read which era a space comes from by its architecture, its tools, its writing on the walls.

1. The Salt Mine (centuries before the Order)
A working salt mine carved into a deep deposit. Practical, industrial, abandoned long before any of this began. The miners left because the deposit shifted or the workings became unsafe — the records aren't clear. What they left behind: wide tunnels, old carts, abandoned tools, and millions of tons of salt still in the walls.

2. The Demonologist's Tower (a generation before the Order)
A scholar whose name is partially lost — the Order scratched it from most records, but fragments remain — discovered the abandoned mine and recognized what it was. Not just salt. The single largest natural concentration of salt in the region. Salt is the universal binding agent against demons: it preserves, it draws lines, it cannot be consumed. A demonologist with access to that much salt could draw wards no one else could draw, hold bindings no one else could hold, and — if they were ambitious enough — summon something no one else could summon.

The demonologist built a tower down into the mine, repurposing the mining chambers. Library, laboratory, summoning chamber. They worked in secret for years. They were on the brink of summoning an arch demon — Asch'maroth, the Unmaking — when the Order arrived.

The demonologist had miscalculated. They thought the salt would let them control what they summoned. The salt was already saturated with their working when the Order found them. Asch'maroth was partially manifest — not contained in the summoning circle, not free, but anchored in the deep mine, pulling itself through the boundary one inch per century.

The demonologist died in the confrontation. Their notes survived. The Order read them and understood what they were facing.

3. The Order's Vault (six hundred years and counting)
Sethara, the Order's founder, made the only decision possible. The arch demon could not be banished — it was already too anchored. It could only be contained. And the only material that would hold it was the salt that had drawn it in the first place.

Sethara had the Order shape the entire mine into a containment array: a vast holy symbol carved through the rock, with the demonologist's tower at its dead center, surrounded by walls of refined salt and inscribed wards. The shape itself is part of the working — the Order's holy sigil, immense, formed from the bones of the mine.

This is the Salt Barrier. It is the size of a city.

But salt erodes. Even refined and bound by ritual, the barrier degrades over centuries from the constant pressure of Asch'maroth's slow pull. The Order's solution: a permanent garrison of dead wardens, performing constant maintenance. Knights of the Order, interred upon death, raised as caretakers. Not warriors — masons. Their job is to mine the deep salt, refine it, and patch the barrier where it thins. Every Order knight who dies extends the barrier's lifespan by their own labor in death.

Sethara sealed herself inside as the central anchor — the living will that directs the maintenance, positions the dead, and feels every weakness in the barrier the way a body feels its own wounds.

Why It's Failing Now
The Order on the surface has declined for two generations. Fewer recruits, fewer deaths, fewer bodies interred. But more importantly — the Order has stopped sending salt down.

The original arrangement was symbiotic: living members on the surface mined and refined surface salt, lowering it into the vault through the mausoleum chimney as raw material for the wardens to use. The wardens could mine salt from the deep veins inside the vault, but those veins are limited and increasingly hard to reach. Surface salt was the bulk supply.

When the surface Order forgot why they were sending salt down, they started cutting back. The chimney has been silent for years.

The wardens improvised. They began digging excursion tunnels — narrow passages out, away from the main entrance, into nearby villages and salt stores. They go out at night. They take what salt they can find. They bring it back. They repair the barrier with it.

This is what alerted the surface: dead things raiding kitchens and salt cellars. The villagers don't understand — they think the dead are attacking them. They're not. The dead are scavenging the only material that's keeping the world from ending.

The Order, hearing the reports, sent Aldric to investigate.

The Zones, Remapped
The four existing zones map cleanly onto the new geography:

Tier 1 — Shallow Graves → The Excursion Tunnels
The narrowest, most recently dug section. Improvised by the wardens to access the surface. The MC enters through the main entrance with Aldric's key, and the first thing they find is that the vault has new construction — tunnels carved by hands that have been dead for decades, hauling salt back inward.

Layout: Narrow corridors, low ceilings, recent excavation. Carts of salt half-loaded and abandoned mid-trip. Skeletons moving in patrol formation along the main corridors (raiding parties returning). Rats in the side passages (followed the dead in from outside).

What the MC sees that doesn't fit their expectations:

The tunnels are new — fresh tool marks, undisturbed dust on the floor where there shouldn't be any
The skeletons aren't wandering aimlessly. They're walking with purpose, in formation, carrying things
One of them is carrying a sack of kitchen salt. Branded. From a town the MC knows.
Sub-areas:

Side storage — Where raiding parties cache their hauls before bringing them deeper. Loot for the player (gold, supplies stolen from villages), but also evidence: the wardens are organized, this is intentional.
The Gate Antechamber — Where the excursion tunnels meet the main vault entrance. The massive original gate is still here, sealed from inside. The MC's key opens a side passage that bypasses it.
Inhabitants: Skeletons (raiders), rats (parasites), the occasional Heap of Bones (raiders that fell apart on the journey).

Tier 2 — The Crypt → The Working Vault
The largest zone. The Order's actual operational space. Mausoleum, library, maintenance halls, barracks. This is where the wardens live — or whatever the dead version of living is. Organized, functional, decaying around the edges.

Sub-areas:

The Mausoleum
Where the dead were prepared and turned. The chimney is the centerpiece — a vast vertical shaft where bodies were lowered from the surface chapter house. It's been silent for years. There's a layer of dust at the bottom that hasn't been disturbed. The preparation room has mortician's tools, salt-curing tables, ritual implements. The transformation chamber has the actual rite circle where the dead were raised into wardens.

Important: There are far fewer tombs in the mausoleum than the MC would expect — because bodies are processed quickly. The mausoleum is a transit space, not a resting place. The wardens it produces leave to take up posts elsewhere in the vault.

The Libraries
Three reading rooms, organized by era:

The Mining Records (oldest) — practical accounts of the salt mine, geological surveys, miners' logs. Mundane until you read them carefully and notice the increasing references to "bad air" and "voices" and "the wrong kind of quiet" in the deepest tunnels.
The Demonologist's Library — what the Order recovered from the tower before sealing it. The demonologist's research, their summoning preparations, their growing certainty that they could control what they were calling. Their final entries are short and frightened.
The Order Archive — Sethara's writings, the construction logs of the Salt Barrier, the maintenance protocols, the names of every warden. This is where the MC starts finding journal entries that paint Sethara as a person, not a monster.
The Artifact Vault (restricted section of the Library)
A locked room behind the Order Archive. Contains items the Order took from the demonologist that were too dangerous to destroy and too valuable to lose. Some are usable — a salt-iron blade, a binding chain, ritual focuses. Some should not be touched. The MC can take what they want, but each item has a reason it was sealed.

Maintenance
A network of work chambers where wardens process salt and repair tools. Stockpiles of refined salt (much smaller than they should be). Mining tools with worn handles. Improvised salt mills (the original equipment broke decades ago). Evidence everywhere of overwork and undersupply. The wardens are doing more with less, and it shows.

The Barracks
Where the wardens organize. Maps of the surface drawn from memory, marked with salt sources. Patrol rotations carved into the walls. Schedules for maintenance shifts. A small chamber where Crypt Stalkers (the elite wardens) plan operations. The MC realizes here, definitively: the dead are running a logistical operation. This is not chaos.

Inhabitants: Skeletons (workers and patrols), Necromancers (foremen — they raise replacement wardens from the rare bodies that still come down), Banshees (in the mausoleum, mourning songs that are part of the interment rite and never stopped), Ghosts (in the library, scholars who never finished their research), the Vampire Lord (a prisoner in a sealed wing of the library — the Order didn't trust any other place to hold him).

Tier 3 — The Lich's Domain → The Inner Containment
The deepest functional zone. The Salt Barrier itself, the Demonologist's Tower at its center, and Sethara's lair beyond.

Sub-areas:

The Salt Barrier
A vast, beautiful, terrifying structure. Walls of compressed salt twenty feet thick, carved with wards, glowing faintly where the salt is fresh and dim where it has thinned. The MC walks the perimeter and sees the failing — patches where wardens have improvised repairs with surface salt of the wrong purity, sections that have been rebuilt three or four times, places where the wall is paper-thin and you can hear something on the other side.

This is also where the Crypt Stalkers are concentrated. They patrol the barrier itself, repairing breaches, killing anything that approaches. They are the elite wardens — former Order knights, the strongest dead, kept fighting-fit because the barrier needs defending as much as maintaining.

The Demonologist's Tower
Built downward into the original mine. The MC enters from above (the Order's level) and descends through the tower. Each floor is a stage of the demonologist's work:

Upper floors: living quarters, library remnants (most was moved to the Order's library)
Middle floors: laboratory, equipment, materials
Lower floors: the summoning preparation chambers, ritual diagrams half-erased by Order purification
The lowest floor: the summoning chamber. The interrupted circle. The place where Asch'maroth was anchored. The MC will not enter this chamber until very late — it's behind the Salt Barrier itself.
Sethara's Lair
A small, austere chamber built into the barrier wall. This is where she has been for six centuries. Not a throne room. A workshop. Maps of the barrier covering every surface, marked with thousands of small notations about thinning, repairs, schedules. Her tools. Her chair, which she has not left in living memory.

Inhabitants: Crypt Stalkers (elite barrier patrols), Wailing Shades (undead corrupted by proximity to the barrier — wardens whose constant work near the breach has begun to hollow them out), Necromancers (the most senior, who oversee barrier repair operations), Sethara herself.

Side Tier — Kitchen Sink → The Old Salt Mines
The original mine, predating everything. Outside the barrier — behind the Order's containment from the geographic perspective, but the Order never bothered to fully integrate it because it was too unstable and too far from the breach. It's structurally part of the same network of caves but functionally separate.

Why go here:

Untapped salt veins — The richest source of refinement-grade salt in the vault. The wardens have stopped mining it because the routes are too dangerous and too far. The MC can extract salt here that would take days of refining to produce in the maintenance halls.
The Demonologist's earliest workings — Before the tower was built, the demonologist did preliminary work in the deep mine. Personal journals, early experiments, the moment they first realized what was down here. The most honest account of what Asch'maroth actually is.
The Mining Records' final entries — What the original miners encountered that made them abandon the mine. They knew something was wrong long before the demonologist ever arrived.
Strange things — The salt in these depths has been exposed to Asch'maroth's presence for centuries longer than any other part of the dungeon. Some of it has changed. There are things in the deep mines that aren't undead and aren't demonic and aren't anything the player has a name for.
Inhabitants: Mostly empty. A few warden expedition parties (rare). Wailing Shades around old salt veins. And something else — call it the Mineborn — an emergent enemy that exists nowhere else in the vault. Things grown from salt and dead miners and old contamination. Unique to this zone.

Salt as the Game's Core Resource
Salt replaces and expands the role bone dust played in the previous draft. It's the connective material across every system.

How You Get Salt
Mining — Found in the Maintenance halls, the Old Salt Mines, and (rarely) embedded in the Salt Barrier itself
Refining — Raw salt is heavy and bulky; refined salt is dense and useful. Refinement happens in Cairnsmouth (Tessaly's workshop) or, if the MC unlocks it, in the vault's own maintenance halls
Looting — Salt cellars and salt caches found in raider storage areas, the demonologist's preserved stocks, the Order's emergency reserves
What Salt Does
1. Repairs the Salt Barrier (meta-progression)

The MC can choose to deposit refined salt at maintenance stations along the barrier. This is persistent meta-progress: the barrier's overall integrity is tracked, and depositing salt strengthens it. Strengthening the barrier directly affects the dungeon's behavior — high integrity means fewer Wailing Shades, less ambient pressure, weaker Asch'maroth manifestation; low integrity means everything gets worse, faster.

This creates a brutal core dilemma. Salt has a dozen uses, all of them valuable to the player personally. Or it can be spent on the barrier — which doesn't help the MC directly, but slows the catastrophe.

2. Salt-Coated Weapons

Tessaly can salt-treat any weapon. A salt-coated weapon does bonus damage to demonic-touched enemies (Wailing Shades, Mineborn, certain late-game variants) and applies a dissolution status — interferes with reassembly mechanics. A salt-coated maul kills skeletons permanently and prevents Wailing Shade pulse effects.

3. Salt Lines (placeable consumable)

The MC can pour a line of salt across a doorway. Skeletons and rats won't cross it. Crypt Stalkers will (they're stronger-willed). Wailing Shades cannot. This becomes a tactical tool for managing retreat routes — you sacrifice salt to make a corridor safe for a few expeditions, until the line is disturbed by other traffic or eroded by ambient damp.

4. Salt Lamps

A piece of equipment crafted by Tessaly. A lantern that burns salt slowly, providing light that Shadows cannot drain. Different from the Warden's Lantern — the Salt Lamp consumes salt as fuel (creating a resource cost), but it actively repels Shadows rather than just resisting their drain. Shadows take damage if they approach a lit Salt Lamp.

5. Salt Pouch (worn equipment)

A small leather pouch of salt worn at the waist. Provides minor damage reduction against demonic and corrupted attacks. Salt slowly leaches out — the pouch needs refilling every few expeditions. Cheap, simple, effective.

6. Salt-Iron Weapons (rare crafted)

Found in the Artifact Vault: salt-iron, an alloy the demonologist developed. Tessaly can forge salt-iron weapons if the MC brings her enough raw material. Salt-iron weapons deal damage to enemies that are normally invulnerable — including, eventually, Asch'maroth itself.

7. Sealing Breaches

Where the Salt Barrier has thinned dangerously, the MC can perform a temporary repair using salt and the appropriate inscription. This isn't the same as the meta-repair (which is automated, slow, and large-scale) — this is a personal, immediate seal of a single dangerous breach. Stops Wailing Shades from spawning in adjacent rooms for several expeditions.

The Mystery Layers, Updated
Each zone reveals one major piece of the dungeon's history. The MC pieces the truth together in roughly the order it happened — but discovers it in reverse archaeological order.

Tier 1: Excursion Tunnels — "The dead are organized."
The tunnels are recent. Dug by hand. By the dead.
They're carrying salt back inward.
The MC realizes this isn't a haunted ruin. It's a functioning operation of some kind.
They find the first reference to "the Vault Above" in scratched marks left by raiding parties — implying this isn't the central place. There's somewhere else.
Tier 2: The Working Vault — "The Order is not what we believe."
The Mausoleum reveals the chimney, the preparation room, the rite chamber. The Order makes its dead into wardens.
The Library reveals the three histories: salt mine, demonologist, Order vault.
The MC learns the name Asch'maroth for the first time — in the demonologist's recovered notes, not the Order's records (the Order avoided writing the name).
Sethara's writings reveal her as a person — frightened, determined, exhausted across centuries.
Aldric's journal is found here, abandoned partway through. He had reached the same understanding the MC is now reaching.
The MC begins to understand they are inside a machine that works, badly, and is failing.
Tier 3: The Inner Containment — "What is being held back."
Walking the Salt Barrier, the MC sees the scale of what the Order built. It is breathtaking and crumbling.
The Demonologist's Tower reveals the summoning that was interrupted. The MC sees the circle. They understand what was being called.
Sethara's lair reveals the truth of her position: not a tyrant, not a monster, a workman who has been holding a wall up alone for six centuries.
They reach Asch'maroth. Not the demon itself — that's still behind the barrier. But the breach point, where its presence pushes through hardest. The MC stands a few feet from something that wants to unmake the world, separated by salt that is failing.
And they find Aldric. (His fate revealed here — see below.)
Side Tier: The Old Salt Mines — "This was always wrong."
The original miners abandoned the deep mine because they encountered something. Their final logs are coherent, then frightened, then strange.
The demonologist's earliest journals, written before they fully understood what they were dealing with, are the most honest description of Asch'maroth in the entire dungeon. The Order's records are professional. The demonologist's are afraid.
The MC discovers something the Order never knew: Asch'maroth was already partially present in the mine before the demonologist arrived. The demonologist didn't summon it from nothing. They tried to complete a manifestation that was already happening, slowly, through some natural thinness in the world at the bottom of the mine. The salt deposit wasn't a coincidence — the salt was there because something needed to be contained, long before any human noticed.
This raises the unanswerable question: who put the salt there?
Aldric's Fate
The MC tracks Aldric through the vault:

Excursion Tunnels: A modern boot print. A Vigil sigil scratched into a wall as a marker.
The Working Vault: His abandoned journal, in the Library. He understood what the Order really was. He was reading the Demonologist's research. His handwriting deteriorates over the entries.
The Inner Containment: His equipment near the Salt Barrier. He went past it.
The truth: Aldric reached Sethara. He saw the state of the barrier and understood that the Order on the surface could not save the situation in time. He made a choice. He volunteered for interment. He let Sethara raise him as a warden — the first new warden in a generation, and the freshest, strongest one in the entire grid. The MC finds him standing motionless at a critical junction in the Salt Barrier, in his Vigil armor, eyes open, holding his post. His body is still warm. He's been there for weeks.
The MC can speak to him. He recognizes them — barely, briefly. He says one thing: "The salt. Bring more salt."

This is the moment the MC understands the full scope of what's expected of them. Not heroism. Not victory. Logistics. They are now the surface link in a supply chain, and they came in alone.

The Endings, Updated
The MC has options, gated by what they've learned and what they've chosen to do with the salt they've gathered:

1. Hold the Line

Become the new surface link. Restart the Order's salt supply. Retreat from the dungeon and dedicate the rest of the MC's life to organizing the surface Order around its true purpose. The barrier is stabilized. Asch'maroth remains contained for another generation, maybe two. The MC becomes a quiet warden of an unending watch. Cairnsmouth becomes a logistics hub. The story doesn't end — it becomes maintainable.

2. Take the Anchor

Replace Sethara. The MC has Liturgy training and now has the knowledge. They can take her place at the center of the containment, freeing her at last. They become the new Lich. The barrier holds with fresh will at its center. The MC's personal story ends — they enter the dungeon and never leave. From the surface's perspective, the missing knight stays missing.

3. Banish the Demon

The hardest ending. Requires finding everything: the demonologist's complete summoning method, the Old Salt Mine records, the full understanding of how Asch'maroth was anchored. With this knowledge, the MC can perform a reverse summoning — not banishing the demon from a place, but unmaking the anchor that brought it partway through. This requires a massive amount of salt-iron, all of the Artifact Vault's relics, and the willing cooperation of Sethara herself. If achieved: Asch'maroth is pushed back fully. The barrier is no longer needed. The dead can be laid to rest. The vault becomes a tomb in the truest sense — empty, finished, done. Cairnsmouth loses its purpose and slowly dies. The Order disbands. The MC walks out into a world that no longer needs them, carrying knowledge that should never be needed again.